The interaction method is closely related to the AR hardware used, as shown earlier in Section 3.5.1. Different interaction methods can be used for each hardware type, so the number of 31 interaction forms does not correspond to the number of contributions studied. Seven of the eight identified contributions that use gesture-based control (see Figure 3) can be attributed to the use of AR data glasses [W2531719466, W2670575095, W2892270157, W2984042658, W3039580023, W3047389482, W2990295915]. Of the eleven papers that use touch interaction, four are attributed to the use of a smartphone [W2531719466, W2976341962, W3158684294, UNMAPPED:65] and five to the use of a tablet [W2800214149, W2990639944, W2976341962, W2286155249, W2896431518, UNMAPPED:67]. Stigall and Sharma [W2976341962] used both a smartphone and a tablet. Another form of interaction includes direct interaction with virtual objects, which was described in five papers [W2811068961, W2949393039, W3158684294, W2990295915, UNMAPPED:55].

